Milestone Report

Marcos Antonio Ribeiro

March 22, 2016.

Overview

The goal of this report is an exploratory analysis of some text documents in order to build a prediction model to be used in predicting the next word to be typed, so the user will get some help in typing when using mobile devices.

About the exploration

We are going to use the dfm function from quanteda package to clean our data and create the document feature matrix.

Our cleaning process consists of:
1 transforming the data to lowercase;
2 remove numbers, punctuation, separators.

As we intend to predict typing, we will not remove stop words and will not stem words. Also, profanity words will not be removed in order to not decrease the prediction accuracy, Id rather filter them after prediction. In this case, its important to keep all the words in a prediction model to get a better accuracy. Its common to use some foreign expression, so also, we wont remove them.

Files to be explored:

1 en_US.blogs.txt
2 en_US.news.txt
3 en_US.twitter.txt

Functions to get word frequency and compute score over all words

    # Create a data frame with the frequency of each word and the percentage compared to the total of words
    word_freq <- function(x) {
        # Get the sum of each word and sort in decreasing order
        freq <- colSums(x)
        freq <- sort(freq, decreasing=TRUE)

        # Count the total of words in the corpus
        countw <- sum(x)

        # Get the list of words
        word <- names(freq)

        # Calculate the percentage of words (terms) among all of words in the corpus
        rate <- lapply(freq, function(x) round(x[]/countw,4) )

        # Returning a table with word (term), frequence and percentage
        f2 <- cbind(word, freq, rate )
        return(f2)
    }

    # Compute the number of words needed to reach a given percentage of the total words.
    count_score <- function(freq, p) {
        sum_rating <- 0
        count <- 0
        while (sum_rating<p) {
            count<-count+1
            sum_rating <- sum(as.numeric(freq[1:count,3]))
        }
        return(count)
    }
